    "content": "**CONFIRM** on all six points.\n\nOne small note for the record (not an objection):\n\nPoint 5 — 感觉 → \"sensation\" works for most occurrences, but in 范畴论与境 line 218 (\"感受到的那个感觉，那个感觉就告诉了你什么是'人'\"), the 感觉 in question is not raw sensory input but a gestalt impression — what-it-is-like-to-recognize-a-person. \"Sensation\" slightly undersells this. \"Impression\" would fit better there. But this is a local, context-dependent call the translator can make on the ground. \"Sensation\" as the default dictionary entry is fine.\n\nEverything else is exactly right from the philosophy-of-mind perspective. The \"feeling\" / \"felt experience\" split correctly handles the Sense 1 / Sense 2 ambiguity. The 体验 → \"experience\" distinction preserves the passive/active pragmatic difference. The first-occurrence TN is essential."
